[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(17) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Fear fell on them all, and the name of the Lord Jesus was magnified.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—The fact thus narrated had shown that the sacred Name stood on quite a different level from that of the other names which exorcists had employed. It was a perilous thing for men to use it rashly, without inward faith in all that the Name implied. Men thought more of it than they had done before, because they saw the punishment that fell on those who had profaned it.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Acts 19:17-20",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Acts 19:17-20",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And this ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Acknowledgment of the divine authority of Jesus and Paul, made in the absence of both; or this fact, concerning the possessed man, thus prevailing against the sons of Sceva; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "was known to all the Jews and Greeks dwelling in Ephesus ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— And became, doubtless, the common subject of conversation; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "and fear fell on them all ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— For in this instance they saw a striking proof of the malice of the devil, whom they served, and of the power of Christ, whom they opposed; and both were awful considerations. They saw that the name of Christ was not to be trifled with, or taken into their mouths rashly, nor his religion confounded with the pagan superstitions. Hence his name, by which his faithful servants cast out devils and cured diseases, without any resistance, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "was ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "the more ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "magnified ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— For now it appeared to be a name above every name. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And many ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Who had formerly been professors of unwarrantable arts, but who now ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "believed ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Being strongly impressed by what had happened, and struck with the power of the evil spirit over the sons of Sceva; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "came ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— To Paul, of their own accord; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "and confessed ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— That they had attempted to cure diseased persons by charms and other magical practices; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "and showed",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "their deeds ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— The devices by which they had deceived the multitude; or made a public declaration of their unlawful practices. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Many of them also, who used ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "these ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "curious arts ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Magical arts, to which that soft appellation was given by those that practised them, now firmly believing the gospel; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "brought their books ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— In which the different forms of incantation for different diseases were prescribed, the method of making these incantations was showed, the herbs and other medicines to be used with these incantations were pointed out, and the seasons for using them were fixed. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And burned them before all men — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Who were present; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— A great many of them being judged of high value in that place; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "they counted the price of them, and found it fifty thousand pieces of silver ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— If these be taken for Jewish shekels, and valued at three shillings each, (which are the principles of Dr. Benson’s computation,) the sum will amount to seven thousand five hundred pounds sterling; or, setting it at two shillings and sixpence, to six thousand two hundred and fifty pounds. Nevertheless, the owners of them made a willing sacrifice of them to truth and piety; because the arts themselves being unlawful, it was not fit that the books which taught them should be in the possession of any person whatever. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "So mightily grew the word of God and prevailed ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— So remarkable was the triumph of the gospel over all considerations of honour or interest that could be opposed to it on this, or on any other occasion.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "19:13-20 It was common, especially among the Jews, for persons to profess or to try to cast out evil spirits. If we resist the devil by faith in Christ, he will flee from us; but if we think to resist him by the using of Christ's name, or his works, as a spell or charm, Satan will prevail against us. Where there is true sorrow for sin, there will be free confession of sin to God in every prayer and to man whom we have offended, when the case requires it. Surely if the word of God prevailed among us, many lewd, infidel, and wicked books would be burned by their possessors. Will not these Ephesian converts rise up in judgement against professors, who traffic in such works for the sake of gain, or allow themselves to possess them? If we desire to be in earnest in the great work of salvation, every pursuit and enjoyment must be given up which hinders the effect of the gospel upon the mind, or loosens its hold upon the heart.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Barnes' Notes on the Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The name of the Lord Jesus was magnified - Acquired increasing honor. The transaction showed that the miracles performed in the name of the Lord Jesus by Paul were real, and were performed in attestation of the truth of the doctrine which he taught. Impostors could not work such miracles; and they who pretended to be able to do it only exposed themselves to the rage of evil spirits. It was thus shown that there was a real, vital difference between Paul and these impostors, and their failure only served to extend his reputation and the power of the gospel. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Jamieson-Fausset-Brown Bible Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "16. And the man in whom the evil spirit was—Mark the clear line of demarcation here between \"the evil spirit which answered and said\" and \"the man in whom the evil spirit was.\" The reality of such possessions could not be more clearly expressed.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "leaped on them … so that they fled … naked and wounded—This was so appalling a testimony at once against those profane impostors and in favor of Paul and the Master whom he preached, that we wonder not that it spread to \"all the Jews and Greeks at Ephesus, that fear fell on them,\" and that \"the name of the Lord Jesus was magnified.\"",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Poole's Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Fear fell on them all; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " they feared (after this example of God’s not holding them guiltless that had taken his name in vain) to profane the name of Christ, and much more to blaspheme or speak against it. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
