  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Meyer's NT Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 19:17-18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The first impression of this signal miscarriage of that application of the name of Jesus was in the case of the Ephesian multitude naturally ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "fear, dread",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (see on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 2:43",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") on account of its extraordinary nature (on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἐπέπεσε φόβος",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 1:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); and then followed universal praise of that name (comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 7:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And many who",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (through this event now) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "were believers",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "τῶν πεπιστ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".[94]) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "came",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (to Paul) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "and confessed and made known",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (an exhaustive description) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "their deeds",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". This open confession (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἐξομολ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "., see on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 3:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") of their previous practices, which had been entirely alien and opposed to the faith in Christ, was the commencement of their new life of faith. In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "πολλοί",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "τὰς πράξ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "αὐτ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". the converted sorcerers and their evil tricks are meant to be ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "included",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", but not they ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "only",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (in opposition to Heinrichs and Olshausen); for it is not till ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 19:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " that these exclusively are treated of. As to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "πράξεις",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " in a bad sense, comp. on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Romans 8:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
